While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to the removal of nuclear weapons, according to which North Korea will be rewarded if it takes gradual steps, his words seemed significant in that it did not unconditionally reject the unilateral removal of nuclear weapons.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim undertook to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula" while Trump assured North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. is pushing for the "destruction of nuclear weapons first" and exerting more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way, and even objecting to the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can force us to our knees is a dream of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our distrust."
Ri said nothing about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader drew attention to earlier in the week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings during the past five months between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in, adding: "If the party in this issue on nuclear weapons destruction was South Korea and not the US, the destruction of nuclear weapons would not have reached such a point in the Korean Peninsula."
The tone of Ri's speech, however, was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's missiles would be aimed at the U.S. landmass after "Mr. Bose President" Trump called Kim a "fireman" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, lavished praise on Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but he said much work still needs to be done and that sanctions should remain there until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
