A new course at Harvard University this year allows all of its undergraduate students to get more sleep in an attempt to counter the growing macho culture of studying by caffeine-fueled 'all-night sessions'.
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often dishonest when it comes to the basic principles of how to look after themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one has ever told her how important sleep is - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how they improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to enter the course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The hour-long course involves a few interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a dormitory, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to be told about the effect of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know this won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know what the health effect of choosing to smoke cigarettes is," Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride to "study all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's "secret weapon" should be to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even to avoid putting on weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a mode of starvation, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after he attended one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to strive for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when they are going to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and lead you to succumb to it.
