The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the crown when Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team scored the 14.5 points they needed to win the United States.
U.S. star Phil Mickelson, who struggled for most of the tournament, had his T-shirt blown in the water at the par-3 16th hole and conceded his game to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari blinked in all his rounds and became one of the 1-of-4 players to ever go 5-0-0 since the tournament's current format began in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was blown out 5&4 by the player with the lowest rank on the European team, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The player with the world's highest ranking, Dustin Johnson, fell 2 and 1 to land Poulter of England who may have played in his final Ryder Cup.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spaniard Sergio Garcia, has become the tournament's European winner of all time with 25.5 career points.
"I don't usually cry, but today I can't help it.
It's been a rough year.
Thank you so much for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad I got the cup back.
It's about the team and I'm glad I could help," said an emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He hands the torch over to his compatriot John Ram who on Sunday beat US-based Tiger Woods 2&1 in a single game.
"The incredible pride I feel in winning Tiger Woods, I've grown up and looked after those guys," Rahm said.
Woods has lost all four of his games in France and now has a record of 13-21-3 career Ryder Cup record.
A strange statistic by one of the greatest players of all time and he won 14 major titles second to just Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA struggled throughout the weekend to find the cleanup field with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau who played high-caliber golf throughout the tournament.
US Captain Jim Furyk spoke after a disappointing performance on behalf of his team: "I'm proud of these guys. They fought.
There was a time this morning when we had a little bit of heat in Europe.
We've scrapped it.
Beware of Thomas.
He's a wonderful captain.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We will regroup. I will work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup committee, and we will move forward.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to serve as their captain.
You've got to keep your hat on.
We are overwhelmed."
Latest on Redness: Concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in redeye concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, cholera blooms are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier cities - suggesting reduced concentrations.
In full bloom, the Red Sea extends about 130 miles along the coastline from northern Pinellas to southern Lee cities.
Kolle can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough city, but at fewer locations compared to last week.
Redness is also noted in Pasco city.
Medium concentrations in or near the coast of Pinellas City have been reported in recent weeks, low to high concentrations near the coast of Hillsborough City, background to high concentrations in Manatee City, background to high concentrations in or near the coast of Sarasota City, background to concentric to concentric.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier cities.
Breathing irritation has not been reported in Northwestern Florida in the past week.
